ğŸš€ Docker + Spring Boot Demo
========================================================

This project demonstrates how to:

- Build a simple Spring Boot REST API
- Package it using Maven
- Containerize it with Docker
- Push the image to Docker Hub
- Run it on another machine


========================================================
ğŸ“Œ Prerequisites
========================================================

Install the following tools:

- Java 21
- Maven
- Docker

Verify installation:

    java -version
    mvn -version
    docker --version


========================================================
ğŸ— Step 1 â€“ Create Spring Boot Project
========================================================

Generate a Spring Boot project using:

- Maven
- Java 21
- Spring Web dependency

Project structure:

    demo
     â”œâ”€â”€ src
     â”œâ”€â”€ pom.xml
     â””â”€â”€ Dockerfile


========================================================
ğŸ§© Step 2 â€“ Create Simple REST Controller
========================================================

Create file:

    src/main/java/com/example/demo/HelloController.java

Add the following code:

    package com.example.demo;

    import org.springframework.web.bind.annotation.*;

    @RestController
    @RequestMapping("/")
    public class HelloController {

        @GetMapping
        public String home() {
            return "Hello Docker + Spring Boot ğŸš€";
        }
    }


========================================================
â–¶ Step 3 â€“ Run Application Locally (Without Docker)
========================================================

Run:

    mvn spring-boot:run

Open browser:

    http://localhost:8080

Expected output:

    Hello Docker + Spring Boot ğŸš€

Stop application:

    CTRL + C


========================================================
ğŸ“¦ Step 4 â€“ Build JAR File
========================================================

Build project:

    mvn clean package

Verify JAR exists:

    target/demo-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.jar

Test JAR:

    java -jar target/demo-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.jar

Open browser:

    http://localhost:8080

Stop:

    CTRL + C


========================================================
ğŸ³ Step 5 â€“ Create Dockerfile
========================================================

Create file named: Dockerfile

Add:

    FROM eclipse-temurin:21-jdk-jammy
    WORKDIR /app
    COPY target/demo-0.0.1-SNAPSHOT.jar app.jar
    EXPOSE 8080
    ENTRYPOINT ["java","-jar","app.jar"]


========================================================
ğŸ— Step 6 â€“ Build Docker Image
========================================================

Build image:

    docker build -t demo-app .

Verify image:

    docker images

You should see:

    demo-app    latest


========================================================
â–¶ Step 7 â€“ Run Docker Container
========================================================

Run container:

    docker run -p 8080:8080 demo-app

Open:

    http://localhost:8080

Run in background:

    docker run -d -p 8080:8080 demo-app

Check running containers:

    docker ps

Stop container:

    docker stop <container_id>


========================================================
â˜ Step 8 â€“ Push Image to Docker Hub
========================================================

1) Login:

    docker login

2) Tag image:

    docker tag demo-app yourusername/demo-app:1.0

3) Push image:

    docker push yourusername/demo-app:1.0

Verify repository on Docker Hub website.


========================================================
ğŸ“¥ Step 9 â€“ Run on Another Machine
========================================================

On another system:

    docker login
    docker pull yourusername/demo-app:1.0
    docker run -p 8080:8080 yourusername/demo-app:1.0

Open:

    http://localhost:8080


========================================================
âš  Common Issues & Fixes
========================================================

Port Already Allocated:

If you see:
    Bind for 0.0.0.0:8080 failed

Run using different port:

    docker run -p 9090:8080 yourusername/demo-app:1.0

Open:
    http://localhost:9090


Image Not Found:

If:
    docker pull yourusername/demo-app:1.0
    not found

Push again:

    docker push yourusername/demo-app:1.0


